&gt; Kent Beck wrote:
&gt; &gt; Weiming,
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; I can think of several ways you could write your tests. You could 
&gt; &gt; write the
&gt; &gt; test with an example of a concrete class and use constructors:
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; IMoney addend= new Money(5, &quot;CHF&quot;);
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; You could use factories:
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; IMoney addend= fiveFrancs();
&gt; &gt;   or
&gt; &gt; IMoney addend= MoneyFactory.fiveFrancs();
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; The principle I use in such cases is to defer design 
&gt; decisions as long as
&gt; &gt; possible. I would start with the variables being declared 
&gt; with a concrete
&gt; &gt; class, then introduce interfaces once they would help the code:
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Money addend= new Money(5, &quot;CHF&quot;);
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Sincerely yours,
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Kent Beck
&gt; &gt; Three Rivers Institute
